04027nam a22005775i 9780520958968DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209589687 a10.1525/97805209589682doi  a(DE-B1597)519420  a(OCoLC)880409081  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aGT2850 .F46 2014eb 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a394.1a394.122231 aFerguson, Priscilla Parkhurst, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWord of Mouth :bWhat We Talk About When We Talk About Food /cPriscilla Parkhurst Ferguson. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (302 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in Food and Culture ;v5000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue: Talking About Food -- tPart I. From Talk to Text -- tPart II. New Cooks, New Chefs -- tPart III. The Culinary Landscape in the Twenty-First Century -- tEpilogue: Last Words—Ratatouille -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToday, more than ever, talking about food improves the eating of it. Priscilla Parkhurst Ferguson argues that conversation can even trump consumption. Where many works look at the production, preparation, and consumption of food, Word of Mouth captures the language that explains culinary practices. Explanation is more than an elaboration here: how we talk about food says a great deal about the world around us and our place in it.  What does it mean, Ferguson asks, to cook and consume in a globalized culinary world subject to vertiginous change?  Answers to this question demand a mastery of food talk in all its forms and applications. To prove its case, Word of Mouth draws on a broad range of cultural documents from interviews, cookbooks, and novels to comic strips, essays, and films. Although the United States supplies the primary focus of Ferguson's explorations, the French connection remains vital. American food culture comes of age in dialogue with French cuisine even as it strikes out on its own. In the twenty-first century, culinary modernity sets haute food against haute cuisine, creativity against convention, and the individual dish over the communal meal. Ferguson finds a new level of sophistication in what we thought that we already knew: the real pleasure in eating comes through knowing how to talk about it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFood habitsvCross-cultural studies. 0aFood habitsxCross-cultural studies. 0aFoodvCross-cultural studies. 0aFoodxCross-cultural studies. 0aFoodxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095896840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958968423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958968/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles